Thank you.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:05.610 align:middle line:84%
>> I think you're in a unique
line of work in that you are

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:09.780 align:middle line:84%
experimenting with the work
yourself and using people

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:11.310 align:middle line:84%
to experiment on
their own lives,

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:14.340 align:middle line:84%
and using life as an opportunity
to discover more of the gifts

00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:16.090 align:middle line:90%
that people have.

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:18.690 align:middle line:84%
And I see that in
your work, you're

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:21.200 align:middle line:90%
constantly seeking to evolve.

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:24.120 align:middle line:84%
But one of the first areas
that I want to speak about

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:28.980 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit about the
cultural sort of environment

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:30.900 align:middle line:84%
that we've found
ourselves in the midst

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:33.040 align:middle line:90%
of in this particular time.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:36.960 align:middle line:84%
We have developed what
we sort of call in some

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:39.030 align:middle line:84%
circles an acronym,
a weird culture,

00:01:39.030 --> 00:01:42.150 align:middle line:84%
a Western-educated,
industrialized, rich and

00:01:42.150 --> 00:01:43.680 align:middle line:90%
democratic world.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.930 align:middle line:90%
I think I got the spacing right.

00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:48.720 align:middle line:84%
And that has created
an environment

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:53.160 align:middle line:84%
where we've seemed to place
material possessions and wealth

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:56.970 align:middle line:84%
accumulation above
family, above friends,

00:01:56.970 --> 00:02:00.030 align:middle line:84%
and we've isolated ourselves
in our wealthy houses up

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:00.970 align:middle line:90%
on the hill.

00:02:00.970 --> 00:02:05.610 align:middle line:84%
You've worked with many of
these people at great cost.

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:07.440 align:middle line:84%
What do you think
some of the biggest

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.620 align:middle line:84%
downfalls of this system are
in terms of people's happiness,

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:13.320 align:middle line:90%
health, and well-being?

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:16.230 align:middle line:84%
>> I think a lot of the
social constructs that have

00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:17.630 align:middle line:90%
historically been around--

00:02:17.630 --> 00:02:19.213 align:middle line:84%
I mean, even if I
think about Ireland,

00:02:19.213 --> 00:02:22.320 align:middle line:84%
a small island
where I grew up, we

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:24.030 align:middle line:90%
put bank managers on pedestals.

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:26.400 align:middle line:84%
We put financial
institutions on pedestals.

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:27.570 align:middle line:90%
We were fearful of them.

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:30.050 align:middle line:84%
We gave them way
too much respect.

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:31.590 align:middle line:84%
If you go back to
the early '70s,

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:35.040 align:middle line:84%
if you walk down the
pathway or the sidewalk

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:38.460 align:middle line:84%
and a priest came towards you,
you would step off the pavement

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:40.440 align:middle line:90%
and allow the priest to pass.

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:44.100 align:middle line:84%
And as the banking
system has been shaken

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.920 align:middle line:84%
and as people have taken
the bank managers literally

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:51.560 align:middle line:84%
off pedestals, as Catholicism
in Ireland has been shaken

00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:54.620 align:middle line:84%
and people are choosing, for
example, not to go to church,

00:02:54.620 --> 00:02:56.940 align:middle line:84%
it's leaving some
sort of vacuum.

00:02:56.940 --> 00:03:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And it's leaving people
isolated to some extent

00:03:02.190 --> 00:03:05.850 align:middle line:84%
and searching for
community on Facebook.

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:08.410 align:middle line:84%
And yes, Facebook groups
and Facebook communities,

00:03:08.410 --> 00:03:09.570 align:middle line:90%
some of them are very good.

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:12.360 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes they're no
more than a Facebook group.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:14.100 align:middle line:84%
And people are moving
into these places

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:19.110 align:middle line:84%
online, looking for
a village of people,

00:03:19.110 --> 00:03:22.470 align:middle line:84%
looking for a community,
and not necessarily feeling

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:27.370 align:middle line:84%
the spiritual connective
tissues that they want

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:29.250 align:middle line:90%
or connectivity that they want.

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:31.800 align:middle line:84%
And then they're left
looking in the mirror going,

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:33.150 align:middle line:90%
the community's not the problem.

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:34.920 align:middle line:90%
I'm the problem.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:36.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm the issue here.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.180 align:middle line:90%


00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.320 align:middle line:84%
And I feel that we're in
a world right now where

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.110 align:middle line:84%
the greatest pandemic is
isolation and loneliness.

00:03:44.110 --> 00:03:47.350 align:middle line:84%
And you can have 5,000 Facebook
friends, 25,000 Twitter

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:51.560 align:middle line:84%
followers, and yet feel very
lonely within your own skin.

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:54.535 align:middle line:10%
And I feel that that is one
of the biggest things that

00:03:54.535 --> 00:03:56.233 align:middle line:10%
is haunting humanity.

00:03:56.233 --> 00:03:57.775 align:middle line:84%
And what a lot of
people are doing is

00:03:57.775 --> 00:04:00.100 align:middle line:84%
they're trying to replace
that with achievement,

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:02.980 align:middle line:90%
and it simply is not working.

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.890 align:middle line:84%
>> An interesting point you
raise is about social media.

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:10.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we have given away a lot
of our self-worth and our value

00:04:10.450 --> 00:04:11.590 align:middle line:90%
to social media.

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:16.600 align:middle line:84%
And people will look
to likes and views

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.910 align:middle line:90%
as a sense of self-worth.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.670 align:middle line:84%
And that is leading the world
in quite a tricky predicament

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:24.310 align:middle line:84%
in that the younger generation,
or even this current generation

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:27.828 align:middle line:84%
that's alive now
are externalizing

00:04:27.828 --> 00:04:30.370 align:middle line:84%
their self-worth as opposed to
building that from the inside.

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:32.010 align:middle line:84%
Is that something you'd say
you've witnessed in your work?

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:33.173 align:middle line:90%
>> I see it all the time.

00:04:33.173 --> 00:04:34.090 align:middle line:90%
I see it all the time.

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:36.160 align:middle line:84%
We're looking for that
external recognition.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:38.770 align:middle line:84%
And I'm working with
clients every single day

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:41.320 align:middle line:84%
that have climbed that
mountain, the mountain

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:43.545 align:middle line:84%
of societal success,
financial success.

00:04:43.545 --> 00:04:44.920 align:middle line:84%
And they've climbed
the mountain.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:45.550 align:middle line:90%
They get to the top.

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:48.133 align:middle line:84%
They look around, and they just
feel-- they feel an emptiness.

00:04:48.133 --> 00:04:51.232 align:middle line:84%
And as you and I have discussed
before, rather than stopping

00:04:51.232 --> 00:04:53.440 align:middle line:84%
and saying, what are I
missing, what am I not seeing,

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:55.360 align:middle line:84%
what is the question
I'm avoiding,

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:57.610 align:middle line:84%
what is the part of me that
I'm afraid the world will

00:04:57.610 --> 00:04:59.560 align:middle line:84%
see, we just come
down off the mountain,

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:01.900 align:middle line:84%
climb another mountain,
and keep repeating

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:04.870 align:middle line:84%
the same internal pattern
and getting exactly

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:07.110 align:middle line:84%
the same result. All
the time I see it.

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:10.140 align:middle line:90%
I see it every single day.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.870 align:middle line:84%
>> Would you say that the
way that we've been taught

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:15.330 align:middle line:84%
to parent in the West could
be contributing to that?

00:05:15.330 --> 00:05:16.860 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I've spoken
to people who

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:22.730 align:middle line:84%
have built a business, made huge
amounts of monetary success,

00:05:22.730 --> 00:05:26.007 align:middle line:84%
pleased their parents to
no end, and then realized

00:05:26.007 --> 00:05:27.590 align:middle line:84%
they were only doing
it because that's

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:29.030 align:middle line:90%
how they were loved as a child.

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:30.540 align:middle line:84%
They were loved when
they were successful.

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:31.970 align:middle line:84%
They were loved when
they got good grades.

00:05:31.970 --> 00:05:33.595 align:middle line:84%
And they translated
that to, well, I'll

00:05:33.595 --> 00:05:36.215 align:middle line:90%
be loved when I'm wealthy.

00:05:36.215 --> 00:05:38.340 align:middle line:84%
And then when they realize
they've been doing that,

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:39.923 align:middle line:84%
it just brings their
whole world down.

00:05:39.923 --> 00:05:41.300 align:middle line:90%
And they're like, whoa.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:42.320 align:middle line:90%
Who am I to be now?

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:44.280 align:middle line:84%
Is that the sort of thing
you're talking about?

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:45.080 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:48.290 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I think it's spoken
expectations from our parents,

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:51.050 align:middle line:84%
but I think where I
tend to focus a lot on

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:53.730 align:middle line:90%
is the unspoken expectations.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:56.120 align:middle line:84%
So for example, the little
analogy or story that I use

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:59.000 align:middle line:84%
is, you know, the father comes
down to the kitchen table,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.220 align:middle line:84%
and Johnny's about
to go to school

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:04.720 align:middle line:84%
and choose whatever college
he's about to go after.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And his father has
verbalized how much

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:11.502 align:middle line:84%
he disdains parents that put
their kids under pressure.

00:06:11.502 --> 00:06:12.460 align:middle line:90%
And he turns to Johnny.

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:13.960 align:middle line:84%
He says, Johnny,
you can do whatever

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:16.550 align:middle line:84%
you want with your
life, and Mom and myself

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:18.300 align:middle line:90%
will be so proud of you.

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:21.040 align:middle line:84%
Now I was a postman and your
grandfather was a postman,

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:22.898 align:middle line:84%
but you go do whatever
you want to do.

00:06:22.898 --> 00:06:25.190 align:middle line:84%
And he goes to the golf course
and he tells his buddies

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:26.190 align:middle line:90%
that he just had a chat.

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.910 align:middle line:84%
But Johnny goes to
school that day,

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:35.400 align:middle line:84%
wishing and praying and
dreaming about being a pilot.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:37.530 align:middle line:84%
But actually, he yearns
the love of his father

00:06:37.530 --> 00:06:40.320 align:middle line:84%
and the approval of his father,
and he's haunted by the fact

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:42.810 align:middle line:84%
that his father has
gifted him this idea

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:45.720 align:middle line:84%
that really if you want me
to love you and accept you

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:49.710 align:middle line:84%
beyond measure, you
should be a postman.

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:51.090 align:middle line:90%
But he didn't say that.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:53.460 align:middle line:90%
It's the unspoken expectations.

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:57.950 align:middle line:84%
And when you delve into
that, when you are parented,

00:06:57.950 --> 00:07:01.580 align:middle line:84%
it can show you a lot of
what drives you today,

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:05.210 align:middle line:84%
and it can really help you
understand your narrative.

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:06.513 align:middle line:90%
And it's not right or wrong.

00:07:06.513 --> 00:07:07.430 align:middle line:90%
It just is what it is.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:10.370 align:middle line:84%
But it allows you then to pivot
a little bit sooner in life

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:14.270 align:middle line:84%
rather than waiting till you're
90 years old to discover it.

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:17.730 align:middle line:84%
>> This sort of plays into that
idea that we are meaning making

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:18.530 align:middle line:90%
machines, right?

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:23.777 align:middle line:84%
We tend to place and create
meaning out of experiences.

00:07:23.777 --> 00:07:25.610 align:middle line:84%
So this is an example
of someone who created

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:26.693 align:middle line:90%
meaning out of experience.

00:07:26.693 --> 00:07:29.030 align:middle line:84%
My dad said do
this, but deep down,

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:31.040 align:middle line:84%
what I understood
to be true is that I

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:36.320 align:middle line:84%
should be a postman if I want
to follow my dad's role in life.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.800 align:middle line:84%
As parents or as
children, how can we

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.660 align:middle line:84%
be more aware of
those sort of meanings

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:43.050 align:middle line:90%
we're placing on situations?

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:43.850 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:45.410 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's something
I struggle with.

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:47.077 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I struggle
with a lot of things.

00:07:47.077 --> 00:07:49.460 align:middle line:84%
But the thing I struggle
with most is parenting.

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:51.068 align:middle line:90%
It's just a constant.

00:07:51.068 --> 00:07:53.360 align:middle line:84%
And just when you think you're
just achieving something

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:56.030 align:middle line:84%
very effectively, it just
comes back to bite you.

00:07:56.030 --> 00:07:58.130 align:middle line:84%
The only thing that I
have found to work truly

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:02.090 align:middle line:84%
as a parent is honestly
allowing my kids to see

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:06.650 align:middle line:84%
my vulnerabilities,
is to truthfully share

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:08.840 align:middle line:84%
where my fears lie
when I come back

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:10.910 align:middle line:84%
after a keynote or workshop
that didn't go well

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:13.490 align:middle line:84%
is to sit down and talk my
kids, if they're interested.

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:15.620 align:middle line:84%
And recently, we had
an example of this

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:18.938 align:middle line:84%
where my little girl with a
few the neighbors-- they're all

00:08:18.938 --> 00:08:20.480 align:middle line:84%
eight years old--
decided that they'd

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:23.930 align:middle line:90%
fill the mailboxes with rocks.

00:08:23.930 --> 00:08:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And they did two or three, and
then my little girl felt guilty

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:28.000 align:middle line:90%
and she came home.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And she said to her brother,
Charlie, who's my son who's 10,

00:08:30.500 --> 00:08:31.300 align:middle line:90%
she said, listen.

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:33.230 align:middle line:84%
I did this, and I
feel really bad.

00:08:33.230 --> 00:08:35.900 align:middle line:84%
And just about two weeks
earlier, I basically

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:37.742 align:middle line:84%
had this conversation
with my kids

00:08:37.742 --> 00:08:39.159 align:middle line:84%
where I shared
stuff that I'd done

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:40.250 align:middle line:90%
that I'm not very proud of.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:41.583 align:middle line:90%
And my wife was like, oh my god.

00:08:41.583 --> 00:08:43.400 align:middle line:84%
I can't believe
you're sharing this.

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:44.720 align:middle line:90%
And the kids were mesmerized.

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:47.358 align:middle line:84%
They just couldn't believe that
Dad was sharing all this stuff

00:08:47.358 --> 00:08:48.900 align:middle line:84%
that he'd done that
he's not proud of

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:51.440 align:middle line:90%
and that was bad or bold.

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.080 align:middle line:84%
And Charlie turns to Maggie
in the moment of guilt

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:56.630 align:middle line:84%
that she was feeling about
filling the mailboxes of rocks,

00:08:56.630 --> 00:08:58.680 align:middle line:84%
which is not a very serious
thing when you think about it,

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:00.020 align:middle line:90%
and says, you should tell Dad.

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:00.980 align:middle line:90%
She goes, Dad?

00:09:00.980 --> 00:09:03.200 align:middle line:84%
He's the one guy I'm
not going to tell.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:05.792 align:middle line:84%
And Charlie goes back and
says, you should tell Dad.

00:09:05.792 --> 00:09:08.000 align:middle line:84%
Remember a couple of weeks
ago, the stuff he told us?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.415 align:middle line:90%
He's done way worse.

00:09:10.415 --> 00:09:12.290 align:middle line:84%
And the two kids came
to me and they sat down

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:14.300 align:middle line:84%
and they explained
what had happened,

00:09:14.300 --> 00:09:15.770 align:middle line:90%
and we just had a chat about it.

00:09:15.770 --> 00:09:18.620 align:middle line:84%
And I find that a lot
of parents is we're

00:09:18.620 --> 00:09:20.360 align:middle line:90%
trying to protect our kids.

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:22.640 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about
it in a physical sense,

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.680 align:middle line:84%
we put cotton wool
around all the corners

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:27.117 align:middle line:84%
of all the chairs
and everything else,

00:09:27.117 --> 00:09:29.450 align:middle line:84%
and we're trying to overprotect
our kids by not allowing

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:30.890 align:middle line:90%
our kids to see our weaknesses.

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:33.350 align:middle line:84%
We play sports that we're
good at with our children

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:36.380 align:middle line:84%
rather than playing a sport
that we can't play for crap,

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:40.250 align:middle line:84%
and allowing our kids to see
that Dad is miserable at soccer

00:09:40.250 --> 00:09:42.080 align:middle line:90%
or miserable at tennis.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:45.090 align:middle line:84%
And I feel that we're actually
not protecting our kids at all.

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:47.463 align:middle line:84%
We're just simply trying
to protect ourselves.

00:09:47.463 --> 00:09:49.380 align:middle line:84%
We're trying to protect
ourselves emotionally.

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.047 align:middle line:84%
We justify it through
the lens of, well,

00:09:51.047 --> 00:09:52.760 align:middle line:84%
I'm doing the best
for my children.

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:55.250 align:middle line:84%
And then our kids are
brought up in an environment

00:09:55.250 --> 00:09:59.030 align:middle line:84%
where they think their
parents are flawless.

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:00.620 align:middle line:90%
They're superheroes.

00:10:00.620 --> 00:10:03.323 align:middle line:10%
And they go on to emulate
those parents, which

00:10:03.323 --> 00:10:05.240 align:middle line:10%
of course is a catastrophe,
because it's never

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:07.790 align:middle line:10%
going to work.

00:10:07.790 --> 00:10:10.970 align:middle line:84%
>> One of the concepts I heard
you speak about in an interview

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:13.580 align:middle line:84%
that I looked at or
listened to, should I say,

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:18.540 align:middle line:84%
was this idea of somebody
who was in a midlife crisis.

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:20.930 align:middle line:84%
They're working a job for
the last 15 or 20 years

00:10:20.930 --> 00:10:22.730 align:middle line:90%
that they hated.

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:24.920 align:middle line:84%
And they hadn't built up
the strength or courage

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:30.870 align:middle line:84%
to leave or do something that
really followed their passion.

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:34.950 align:middle line:84%
And the excuse that he was
using in this particular example

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:37.590 align:middle line:84%
that he gave was that he was
just doing it for his kids,

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:39.548 align:middle line:84%
to make sure that they
could have enough money,

00:10:39.548 --> 00:10:41.190 align:middle line:84%
to make sure they
could be secure.

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:44.610 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately, when I heard
you telling this story,

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:48.630 align:middle line:84%
I could see that the example
he was setting for his children

00:10:48.630 --> 00:10:51.210 align:middle line:90%
was that, play it safe.

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:53.340 align:middle line:90%
Do something you don't love.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:55.530 align:middle line:90%
Play within the rulebook.

00:10:55.530 --> 00:11:00.030 align:middle line:84%
And ultimately, he was causing
two catastrophes, right?

00:11:00.030 --> 00:11:01.780 align:middle line:84%
How is it that we do
this to our children,

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.370 align:middle line:84%
and do you have any
examples of this?

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:04.170 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:07.800 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if I remember that
correctly, it wasn't until I

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:10.860 align:middle line:84%
said, you know, give me the
name of one of your children--

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:14.220 align:middle line:84%
and let's just say
his child was John.

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:17.520 align:middle line:84%
And I said, if John was
sitting where you are,

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:21.540 align:middle line:84%
describing how painful
it is to go to a job

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:24.990 align:middle line:84%
every single day for, I
believe, 14 years in a row where

00:11:24.990 --> 00:11:27.300 align:middle line:84%
your soul has been diluted
every single moment

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:31.012 align:middle line:84%
of every single day and he was
saying exactly what you were

00:11:31.012 --> 00:11:32.470 align:middle line:84%
saying, and you
were standing here,

00:11:32.470 --> 00:11:33.990 align:middle line:90%
what would you say to him?

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:35.607 align:middle line:90%
And he said, leave.

00:11:35.607 --> 00:11:37.440 align:middle line:84%
Don't waste another day
of your life, buddy.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:40.590 align:middle line:84%
You've got so much
more potential.

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:42.900 align:middle line:90%
And it wasn't until I used--

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:46.440 align:middle line:84%
maybe it's not the right
terminology-- his child for him

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:50.490 align:middle line:84%
to understand what he
was inadvertently doing.

00:11:50.490 --> 00:11:55.720 align:middle line:10%
And he just-- he
couldn't see it.

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:57.430 align:middle line:90%
He just couldn't see it.

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:01.150 align:middle line:84%
He was using his children
as a reason or a rationale

00:12:01.150 --> 00:12:03.103 align:middle line:84%
to stay doing something
that he was doing.

00:12:03.103 --> 00:12:05.020 align:middle line:84%
But in the end of the
day-- and I can tell you

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:08.197 align:middle line:84%
this for absolute certainty--
amongst other things,

00:12:08.197 --> 00:12:10.030 align:middle line:84%
the reason he stays is
not for his children.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:11.470 align:middle line:84%
The reason he stays
is not to put his kids

00:12:11.470 --> 00:12:12.160 align:middle line:90%
to a private school.

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:14.285 align:middle line:84%
And the reason he stays is
not to pay the mortgage.

00:12:14.285 --> 00:12:16.120 align:middle line:84%
The reason he
stays is he doesn't

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:19.780 align:middle line:84%
value himself enough to believe
that he deserves anything

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:22.660 align:middle line:84%
more than a job that is killing
his soul every single day.

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:26.980 align:middle line:84%
And he deprives his children and
humanity of his greatest gifts

00:12:26.980 --> 00:12:28.750 align:middle line:84%
by staying in a job
that just crushes

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.310 align:middle line:90%
his soul every single day.

00:12:30.310 --> 00:12:35.080 align:middle line:84%
And what ends up happening is
that is not a conversation that

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:37.030 align:middle line:90%
can exist in the future.

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:38.290 align:middle line:90%
That becomes a lecture.

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:42.670 align:middle line:84%
Because when dad says to his
young son, don't do that,

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:45.430 align:middle line:84%
don't stay in a job, and
he's done it his entire life,

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:49.390 align:middle line:84%
his son is either internally
or externally going, yeah, Dad.

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:50.410 align:middle line:90%
OK, Dad.

00:12:50.410 --> 00:12:51.550 align:middle line:90%
Are we finished?

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:53.220 align:middle line:84%
Can I get back to
whatever I'm doing?

00:12:53.220 --> 00:12:55.750 align:middle line:84%
But if he's an example of
that, a shining example where

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:59.600 align:middle line:84%
he takes the risk, puts a value
on his own skin, and says,

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:02.440 align:middle line:84%
I am worth more than this,
that conversation won't even

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:03.800 align:middle line:90%
need to happen.

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:07.270 align:middle line:84%
And if it does, his son will
be there, listening intently,

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:09.760 align:middle line:84%
because his father's an
example of everything

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:12.560 align:middle line:90%
that he's discussing.

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:17.250 align:middle line:84%
>> One of the main parts of your
work now is around this concept

00:13:17.250 --> 00:13:19.170 align:middle line:90%
called One Last Talk.

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:21.280 align:middle line:84%
And I know there's going
to be some stories we're

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:22.950 align:middle line:84%
going to hear around
this, but before we

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:25.170 align:middle line:84%
go into any personal
stories that you've shared

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:28.440 align:middle line:84%
or on some topics that
I might ask you about,

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:31.860 align:middle line:84%
what is the concept behind this,
and how did you sort of come up

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:33.090 align:middle line:90%
with this line of work?

00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:34.173 align:middle line:90%
Because it's quite unique.

00:13:34.173 --> 00:13:35.380 align:middle line:90%
Nobody else is doing this.

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:36.797 align:middle line:84%
And how did you
come up with this?

00:13:36.797 --> 00:13:37.650 align:middle line:90%
[SIGH]

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:38.530 align:middle line:90%


00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:41.250 align:middle line:84%
>> I wanted to change
the conversation.

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:43.830 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to challenge
the event space

00:13:43.830 --> 00:13:46.380 align:middle line:84%
where the majority
of live events

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:49.690 align:middle line:84%
are the audience are
sitting in the seats, one

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:52.350 align:middle line:84%
guru or specialist or
expert after another gets up

00:13:52.350 --> 00:13:54.510 align:middle line:84%
there and shares
their success story,

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:56.520 align:middle line:84%
and maybe some
beautiful value as well.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:58.380 align:middle line:90%
How I made it, how I did this.

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:00.180 align:middle line:84%
And often, there's
this undertone

00:14:00.180 --> 00:14:01.430 align:middle line:90%
where people don't discuss it.

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:04.500 align:middle line:84%
As people are leaving, not
feeling motivated or inspired,

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:06.330 align:middle line:84%
they're feeling a
little bit inadequate.

00:14:06.330 --> 00:14:08.670 align:middle line:84%
And I use Richard Branson,
and I say that respectfully,

00:14:08.670 --> 00:14:11.760 align:middle line:84%
because Richard's done some
wonderful things in the world.

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:14.173 align:middle line:84%
But the relatability
was the next thing

00:14:14.173 --> 00:14:15.090 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to challenge.

00:14:15.090 --> 00:14:16.715 align:middle line:84%
How many people can
sit in an audience,

00:14:16.715 --> 00:14:19.020 align:middle line:84%
relate to Richard,
when at his peak

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.860 align:middle line:90%
he had 85,000 staff or a team.

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:24.845 align:middle line:84%
He had his airline,
and so on and so forth.

00:14:24.845 --> 00:14:26.970 align:middle line:84%
And internally-- and I've
interviewed enough people

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:30.180 align:middle line:84%
to know this for fact-- is they
go, yeah, but I can't do that.

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:31.800 align:middle line:90%
He's Richard Branson.

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:33.340 align:middle line:90%
I can't do that.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:36.200 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to
create a platform

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.120 align:middle line:84%
where the people on the
stage are the audience,

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:40.310 align:middle line:90%
and that there is no gurus.

00:14:40.310 --> 00:14:41.970 align:middle line:90%
There is no VIP tickets.

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:44.630 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to prove to
humanity not just does everyone

00:14:44.630 --> 00:14:46.830 align:middle line:84%
have a beautiful,
personal story,

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:48.880 align:middle line:90%
but that that story matters.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:50.522 align:middle line:84%
And when they're
courageous enough

00:14:50.522 --> 00:14:52.230 align:middle line:84%
to share a part of
them that perhaps they

00:14:52.230 --> 00:14:54.510 align:middle line:90%
don't want the world to know--

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:56.610 align:middle line:84%
they share a part of
that they're ashamed of,

00:14:56.610 --> 00:15:00.690 align:middle line:84%
they share a part of themselves
that they're embarrassed by--

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:03.000 align:middle line:84%
they free themselves
of that story.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.820 align:middle line:84%
They heal themselves
of that trauma.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:08.820 align:middle line:84%
And in turn, inadvertently, they
invite the rest of the world

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:10.860 align:middle line:84%
to be healed also,
because somebody

00:15:10.860 --> 00:15:13.620 align:middle line:84%
on the other side of the globe
listens to a One Last Talk,

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:16.980 align:middle line:84%
watches a One Last
Talk, and goes, oh my.

00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:19.560 align:middle line:90%
I'm not alone.

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:21.380 align:middle line:84%
And if he can talk
about his story,

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:25.840 align:middle line:84%
if she can share her story,
maybe I can share mine.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:30.560 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is when healing
happens, connection grows.

00:15:30.560 --> 00:15:33.830 align:middle line:84%
And when connection is there,
it prevents the possibility

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:36.830 align:middle line:90%
of isolation and loneliness.

00:15:36.830 --> 00:15:39.836 align:middle line:84%
And that's why One
Last Talk exists.

00:15:39.836 --> 00:15:42.610 align:middle line:90%
>> Wow.

00:15:42.610 --> 00:15:44.020 align:middle line:84%
Marshall Rosenberg--
I'm not sure

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:45.812 align:middle line:84%
if you're familiar with
his work-- he wrote

00:15:45.812 --> 00:15:48.670 align:middle line:84%
a really seminal piece
of work on communication

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:50.120 align:middle line:90%
called Nonviolent Communication.

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:51.703 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
concepts he talks about

00:15:51.703 --> 00:15:56.410 align:middle line:84%
is understanding somebody's
need or understanding somebody's

00:15:56.410 --> 00:15:58.975 align:middle line:90%
pain and empathizing with it.

00:15:58.975 --> 00:16:03.880 align:middle line:84%
Not solving it, not fixing
it, not creating a solution

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:05.950 align:middle line:84%
or saying, I know a
therapist or I know this.

00:16:05.950 --> 00:16:09.130 align:middle line:84%
Just hearing it,
just understanding it

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:12.653 align:middle line:84%
is healing, and can be
the healing process.

00:16:12.653 --> 00:16:14.320 align:middle line:84%
Is that something
that you subscribe to?

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:16.950 align:middle line:90%
Is that something you've seen?

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:18.940 align:middle line:90%
>> I remember this so clearly.

00:16:18.940 --> 00:16:22.370 align:middle line:84%
We ran a One Last
Talk in Boulder.

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:24.473 align:middle line:84%
And this man called
in a month beforehand.

00:16:24.473 --> 00:16:25.390 align:middle line:90%
He's a client of mine.

00:16:25.390 --> 00:16:29.980 align:middle line:84%
And he said, my son Matthew
is having some challenges.

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:33.280 align:middle line:84%
I'd love him to come
to One Last Talk.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:34.730 align:middle line:90%
How do I get him there?

00:16:34.730 --> 00:16:35.530 align:middle line:90%
I said, tell me.

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:37.080 align:middle line:84%
What are you thinking
of saying or doing?

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:39.550 align:middle line:84%
He said, well, I'm going to
sit him down and give him all

00:16:39.550 --> 00:16:40.808 align:middle line:90%
the reasons why he should go.

00:16:40.808 --> 00:16:42.100 align:middle line:90%
And I said, how does that work?

00:16:42.100 --> 00:16:43.430 align:middle line:90%
And he goes, what do you mean?

00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:45.160 align:middle line:84%
I said, well, how did
that work for you,

00:16:45.160 --> 00:16:46.243 align:middle line:90%
when your father did that?

00:16:46.243 --> 00:16:47.646 align:middle line:90%
He goes, it didn't.

00:16:47.646 --> 00:16:51.920 align:middle line:84%
I said, what if you just sat
down and said, I love you,

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:55.320 align:middle line:84%
I'm scared of losing you, I
don't know what's going on.

00:16:55.320 --> 00:16:57.760 align:middle line:84%
Let me understand you
so I can support you

00:16:57.760 --> 00:16:59.440 align:middle line:84%
or get the hell out
of your own way,

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:00.607 align:middle line:90%
or the hell out of your way.

00:17:00.607 --> 00:17:02.625 align:middle line:90%


00:17:02.625 --> 00:17:04.750 align:middle line:84%
And his son said, I'll
think about it when he said,

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:07.369 align:middle line:90%
would you come to One Last Talk?

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:09.780 align:middle line:84%
And a month later, they
arrived in Boulder,

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:11.543 align:middle line:90%
and his son was 15 years old.

00:17:11.543 --> 00:17:12.960 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of
the event-- he's

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:14.829 align:middle line:84%
not a hugging kid,
according to his father,

00:17:14.829 --> 00:17:16.530 align:middle line:90%
which is interesting.

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:18.500 align:middle line:84%
At the end of the event,
his father comes up,

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:21.000 align:middle line:84%
and this young Matthew appears
behind him and comes straight

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:25.490 align:middle line:84%
up and just launches himself
into my chest and embraces me.

00:17:25.490 --> 00:17:26.310 align:middle line:90%
And I hold him.

00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:29.440 align:middle line:84%
I look behind, and his
father starts to cry.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:32.180 align:middle line:84%
And as we pull apart
from our embrace,

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:33.900 align:middle line:84%
a question I rarely
ask anybody, I

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:36.300 align:middle line:84%
said, what's your number
one takeaway from today

00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:38.970 align:middle line:84%
after watching six
speakers, one after another,

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:41.100 align:middle line:90%
share their one last talk?

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:44.240 align:middle line:84%
He said, it's great to know
that adults have problems too.

00:17:44.240 --> 00:17:47.630 align:middle line:90%


00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:51.710 align:middle line:84%
It's great to know that
adults have problems too.

00:17:51.710 --> 00:17:55.140 align:middle line:84%
Because I think a lot of
parents make their job,

00:17:55.140 --> 00:17:57.890 align:middle line:84%
their mortgage payment,
their investment portfolio

00:17:57.890 --> 00:18:01.880 align:middle line:84%
so massive, so significant--
talk about meaning--

00:18:01.880 --> 00:18:05.150 align:middle line:84%
that a child who's struggling
to connect in the playground

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:07.760 align:middle line:84%
doesn't have the
space, the significance

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.460 align:middle line:84%
to come to Dad or Mom
with the biggest challenge

00:18:10.460 --> 00:18:14.740 align:middle line:84%
that they are facing in
their lives right now,

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:16.985 align:middle line:84%
and to feel that they
can air that and that it

00:18:16.985 --> 00:18:19.160 align:middle line:84%
has significance and
meaning, and that they're OK,

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:21.290 align:middle line:84%
and they're valued
enough in that unit

00:18:21.290 --> 00:18:23.920 align:middle line:90%
to be able to do that.

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:26.210 align:middle line:84%
And in that moment, the
father realized that he just

00:18:26.210 --> 00:18:27.560 align:middle line:90%
doesn't listen to his son.

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:29.960 align:middle line:84%
He's too busy telling him
what he should and should not

00:18:29.960 --> 00:18:32.810 align:middle line:84%
be doing with his life, which
is exactly what his father did

00:18:32.810 --> 00:18:34.070 align:middle line:90%
to him.

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:35.310 align:middle line:90%
And so it continues.

00:18:35.310 --> 00:18:39.360 align:middle line:90%


00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:41.640 align:middle line:84%
>> To bring yourself to
a level of awareness that

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:44.490 align:middle line:84%
you're repeating the patterns
that your parents did

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:48.300 align:middle line:84%
and that's become something that
you're subconsciously now doing

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:52.450 align:middle line:84%
with your children, how do
people come to that awareness

00:18:52.450 --> 00:18:53.250 align:middle line:90%
point?

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:55.417 align:middle line:84%
How have you seen them come
to that awareness point?

00:18:55.417 --> 00:18:57.930 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I'll give you one,
and it's a bit of a fun thing,

00:18:57.930 --> 00:19:00.630 align:middle line:84%
but it's real, is
I often ask people,

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:03.130 align:middle line:84%
which of your parents
are you most like?

00:19:03.130 --> 00:19:06.190 align:middle line:84%
And I often get reactions like,
well, I can tell you one thing.

00:19:06.190 --> 00:19:08.310 align:middle line:90%
I'm definitely not my dad.

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:09.240 align:middle line:90%
There's no doubt.

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:12.210 align:middle line:90%
I'm definitely not my father.

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:13.530 align:middle line:90%
Good luck with that one.

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:16.640 align:middle line:84%
That's most likely who you
are almost identical to.

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:18.930 align:middle line:84%
And the more that you try
to move away from that,

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:21.210 align:middle line:84%
the more you're
emulating your father.

00:19:21.210 --> 00:19:23.190 align:middle line:84%
It's about recognizing
that actually, you're

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:25.020 align:middle line:90%
very similar to your father.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:27.090 align:middle line:84%
It's about integrating
and allowing yourself

00:19:27.090 --> 00:19:30.850 align:middle line:84%
to feel that you're almost
identical in so many ways,

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:32.880 align:middle line:90%
and also unique in many ways.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:37.690 align:middle line:84%
It's about accepting that and
then choosing a different path.

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:41.550 align:middle line:84%
So many parents today
are trying to make

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:45.750 align:middle line:84%
sure that their kids don't get
what they got, or they have

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:47.850 align:middle line:90%
what they didn't have.

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:51.240 align:middle line:84%
And the polar opposite of
that, the other extreme

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:54.110 align:middle line:84%
is that they just continue
to repeat history.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:56.880 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of parents go,
yeah, well, my dad did this,

00:19:56.880 --> 00:19:58.290 align:middle line:90%
and I probably have--

00:19:58.290 --> 00:19:59.490 align:middle line:90%
my kids don't get that.

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:01.740 align:middle line:84%
My natural assumption,
James, all the time

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:04.980 align:middle line:84%
is, I'm passing shit onto my
kids that doesn't serve them.

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:06.340 align:middle line:90%
That's my natural assumption.

00:20:06.340 --> 00:20:10.510 align:middle line:84%
And if I can assume that, that
opens doorways and awareness

00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:14.220 align:middle line:84%
and opportunities for me to
see little subtleties of things

00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:17.520 align:middle line:84%
that I say, if I have to
stop this car-- and I go,

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:18.900 align:middle line:90%
oh, my good god.

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:20.490 align:middle line:90%
That was my dad.

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:23.620 align:middle line:84%
9,000 times a day, it
felt like he said it.

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:25.400 align:middle line:90%
And I go, I'm catching that.

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:27.810 align:middle line:84%
But if I'm in denial of that
reality, if I say to myself,

00:20:27.810 --> 00:20:29.850 align:middle line:84%
no, I'm more aware of
that, my kids don't--

00:20:29.850 --> 00:20:31.735 align:middle line:84%
it's just to assume
every day that you're

00:20:31.735 --> 00:20:34.110 align:middle line:84%
passing on shit to your kids
that is not going to serve--

00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:35.280 align:middle line:90%
that didn't serve you.

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:37.443 align:middle line:90%
That's what we do.

00:20:37.443 --> 00:20:43.080 align:middle line:84%
But don't try to create
this chasm between you

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:45.780 align:middle line:84%
and the dysfunctionality
you saw in your parents.

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.520 align:middle line:84%
Come closer to it
and see the fact

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:49.430 align:middle line:84%
that it's already
there inside of you,

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:50.680 align:middle line:90%
and then you can work with it.

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:51.840 align:middle line:84%
Now you have something
to work with.

00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:52.890 align:middle line:90%
It's like clay.

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:55.020 align:middle line:84%
You can maneuver it and
manipulate it and then

00:20:55.020 --> 00:20:58.510 align:middle line:84%
create something
beautiful out of it.

00:20:58.510 --> 00:21:00.200 align:middle line:84%
>> But that's painful
as shit, right?

00:21:00.200 --> 00:21:02.950 align:middle line:84%
Because that might be a
subtle thing, like, OK.

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:05.350 align:middle line:90%
I'm telling my kids, be quiet.

00:21:05.350 --> 00:21:07.210 align:middle line:90%
Don't make me stop the car.

00:21:07.210 --> 00:21:10.060 align:middle line:84%
OK, that's a subtlety that's
important to be aware of,

00:21:10.060 --> 00:21:11.560 align:middle line:84%
and if you are aware
of that, you're

00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:13.390 align:middle line:84%
able to course correct
and say, hang on.

00:21:13.390 --> 00:21:16.240 align:middle line:84%
How can I give my children
the microphone for a minute

00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:18.670 align:middle line:84%
so they can feel
heard and understood?

00:21:18.670 --> 00:21:20.320 align:middle line:90%
So that's fixable.

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:22.220 align:middle line:90%
What if you were abused?

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:24.400 align:middle line:84%
What if you were
physically abused?

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:26.800 align:middle line:84%
What if you were
sexually abused?

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:28.723 align:middle line:84%
Leaning into that
is not an exercise

00:21:28.723 --> 00:21:29.890 align:middle line:90%
that most people want to do.

00:21:29.890 --> 00:21:32.830 align:middle line:84%
In fact, they spend most of
their life trying to hide that.

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:34.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:38.570 align:middle line:84%
The energy that's expelled
trying to hide that stuff

00:21:38.570 --> 00:21:40.710 align:middle line:90%
is astonishing.

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:44.750 align:middle line:84%
And the way that I use to
describe that is they're

00:21:44.750 --> 00:21:46.400 align:middle line:90%
so used to hiding it.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:50.750 align:middle line:84%
The amount of energy it
takes to hide and suppress

00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:54.900 align:middle line:84%
any type of trauma
is staggering.

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:57.110 align:middle line:84%
And we're living with
it every single day

00:21:57.110 --> 00:21:58.360 align:middle line:90%
that we don't even know.

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:00.470 align:middle line:84%
And the best way I
describe this is my mother

00:22:00.470 --> 00:22:03.795 align:middle line:84%
suffers from significant
arthritis and pain every day.

00:22:03.795 --> 00:22:05.670 align:middle line:84%
And I often ask her,
how are you doing today?

00:22:05.670 --> 00:22:06.503 align:middle line:90%
And she'd go, great.

00:22:06.503 --> 00:22:07.800 align:middle line:90%
Today is a good day.

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:10.320 align:middle line:84%
And if I could get a probe
that could go into my hip--

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:12.320 align:middle line:84%
and could go into her hip
and I could experience

00:22:12.320 --> 00:22:14.720 align:middle line:84%
for two seconds, five seconds
what she's experiencing

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:16.640 align:middle line:84%
in terms of pain,
I'd land on the floor

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:20.580 align:middle line:84%
like a bag of potatoes, and I'd
roll around probably in agony.

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:24.700 align:middle line:84%
But she's been living with
that pain for so long.

00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:26.807 align:middle line:84%
She's been living with
that pain for so long,

00:22:26.807 --> 00:22:28.390 align:middle line:84%
and she's been numbing
it for so long,

00:22:28.390 --> 00:22:32.440 align:middle line:84%
she has no idea of
the energetic cost.

00:22:32.440 --> 00:22:36.070 align:middle line:84%
And I believe that the cost,
the short-term discomfort,

00:22:36.070 --> 00:22:38.530 align:middle line:84%
if you want to call it that,
of addressing a trauma such

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:41.650 align:middle line:84%
as sexual abuse, physical
abuse, mental abuse that you

00:22:41.650 --> 00:22:47.100 align:middle line:84%
experienced as a child,
the short-term discomfort--

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:49.450 align:middle line:84%
it's the tip of the iceberg
when it comes to living

00:22:49.450 --> 00:22:51.100 align:middle line:90%
with that every single day.

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:55.150 align:middle line:84%
Because again, your
soul is depressed.

00:22:55.150 --> 00:22:57.040 align:middle line:90%
Your spirit is squashed.

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:58.210 align:middle line:90%
You don't get to amplify.

00:22:58.210 --> 00:22:59.320 align:middle line:90%
You don't get to show up.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:01.390 align:middle line:84%
You don't get to share
all of who you are.

00:23:01.390 --> 00:23:07.150 align:middle line:84%
And if you think for a moment
that by me hiding my trauma,

00:23:07.150 --> 00:23:09.550 align:middle line:84%
by me not talking about it
I'm protecting everybody else,

00:23:09.550 --> 00:23:11.080 align:middle line:90%
you're living in a cloud.

00:23:11.080 --> 00:23:14.830 align:middle line:84%
You're living on Mars, because
your kids are feeling it

00:23:14.830 --> 00:23:17.080 align:middle line:90%
energetically every single day.

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:18.610 align:middle line:84%
They're not sitting
there going, why

00:23:18.610 --> 00:23:23.350 align:middle line:84%
is Mom not as alive as
my friend Albert's mom?

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:26.230 align:middle line:90%
Where's the spark in her face?

00:23:26.230 --> 00:23:28.360 align:middle line:84%
My mother-- and I've
never shared this before--

00:23:28.360 --> 00:23:29.350 align:middle line:90%
but my mother was--

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:32.750 align:middle line:90%


00:23:32.750 --> 00:23:36.150 align:middle line:84%
my mother was sexually abused
by a priest in Ireland.

00:23:36.150 --> 00:23:40.410 align:middle line:84%
And I always knew there
was something there.

00:23:40.410 --> 00:23:44.240 align:middle line:84%
I always knew there
was something there.

00:23:44.240 --> 00:23:47.032 align:middle line:84%
She's so beautiful,
so intuitive.

00:23:47.032 --> 00:23:48.240 align:middle line:90%
But I always knew there was--

00:23:48.240 --> 00:23:50.750 align:middle line:84%
I always wondered, why
does she not trust herself?

00:23:50.750 --> 00:23:52.760 align:middle line:84%
Why is that intuition
that she has in

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:56.690 align:middle line:84%
abundance that if I do have and
she gifted to me, why isn't she

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:58.730 align:middle line:90%
trusted?

00:23:58.730 --> 00:24:00.410 align:middle line:84%
And I say this with
love and respect.

00:24:00.410 --> 00:24:03.830 align:middle line:84%
My mother doesn't like who
she is, and therefore allows

00:24:03.830 --> 00:24:05.818 align:middle line:84%
herself, her body
to deteriorate.

00:24:05.818 --> 00:24:07.610 align:middle line:84%
And she's never addressed
that in her life.

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:09.473 align:middle line:90%
And that is her choice.

00:24:09.473 --> 00:24:11.390 align:middle line:84%
But as a child growing
up in that environment,

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:12.920 align:middle line:90%
I knew there was something off.

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:14.280 align:middle line:90%
I could feel it.

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:16.780 align:middle line:84%
But it was never spoken about
until one day I turned to her.

00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:19.223 align:middle line:84%
I said, Mom, what do
I not know about you?

00:24:19.223 --> 00:24:20.390 align:middle line:90%
What are you not telling me?

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:24.250 align:middle line:90%


00:24:24.250 --> 00:24:26.680 align:middle line:84%
By holding on to trauma,
you're passing it

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:31.360 align:middle line:84%
on to the next generation
energetically, spiritually.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:33.760 align:middle line:84%
And I know you think you're
doing a good job suppressing

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:34.480 align:middle line:90%
it, but you're not.

00:24:34.480 --> 00:24:36.188 align:middle line:84%
You're doing a shitty
job suppressing it,

00:24:36.188 --> 00:24:37.990 align:middle line:84%
because it's taking
way too much energy,

00:24:37.990 --> 00:24:41.737 align:middle line:84%
and that energy could be
expelled in so many other ways.

00:24:41.737 --> 00:24:43.570 align:middle line:84%
Because when you hide
your negative emotion,

00:24:43.570 --> 00:24:45.940 align:middle line:84%
you high trauma, you hide
your gift in there with it.

00:24:45.940 --> 00:24:48.890 align:middle line:84%
You put it in a box
and lock it away.

00:24:48.890 --> 00:24:52.060 align:middle line:84%
And I believe our greatest gift
lies right next to our deepest

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:53.470 align:middle line:90%
wounds.

00:24:53.470 --> 00:24:55.878 align:middle line:84%
That's what I
believe to my core.

00:24:55.878 --> 00:24:58.420 align:middle line:84%
>> So people listening to this
